article.description: Chamique Holdsclaw played for the first time in three games and scored 27 points as the Mystics posted another dominant offensive effort in an 89-68 victory over the Indiana Fever.
article.headline: Holdsclaw's return sparks Mystics past Fever
article.linkText: Holdsclaw's 27-point return sparks Mystics past Fever
article.story:
WASHINGTON -- Chamique Holdsclaw took control, then let her Washington teammates worry about shutting down ex-Mystics star Nikki McCray.

Holdsclaw came back to the lineup with 27 points and the Mystics
spoiled McCray's return to the MCI Center with an 89-68 victory
over the Indiana Fever on Friday night.

"I'm probably the name that everybody recognizes, but in this
league one player is not going to go out and lead a team to a
championship,'' said Holdsclaw, who missed the past two games after
attending her grandmother's funeral in New York.

Stacey Dales-Schuman added 13 points and reserve Helen Luz
scored 12 points as Washington won its second consecutive game.

Tamika Catchings and Olympia Scott-Richardson scored 15 points
to lead the Fever.

McCray, the first player allocated to the Mystics in their
history, was traded to Indiana on Dec. 5, 2001. She received a warm
ovation when introduced, but was barely a factor until the game was
already decided and finished with 12 points.

"It felt weird, but it also felt good to get a standing
ovation,'' McCray said. "To be honest, I didn't know how they were
going to react.''

Washington used an up-tempo game to take a 50-33 lead at
halftime. The 50-point effort matched the highest-scoring first
half in franchise history.

McCray's lone basket of the first half, a 3-pointer from the
left side, cut Washington's lead to 10-9 with 16:26 remaining in
the first half. But the Mystics responded with a 15-4 run as the
Fever missed their next seven shots.

Six Washington players scored during the burst, which ended with
Helen Luz's 3-pointer and a 26-13 lead.

Holdsclaw, who scored six points in the run, was happy that she
wasn't the Mystics' only option as they broke open the game.

"It's about being more mature and reading defenses,'' Holdsclaw
said. "If one player is covered, I'm confident enough that I can
kick it to Stacey or Vicki (Bullett).''

   That's the type of multi-player attack that Washington coach
Marianne Stanley says the Mystics need to develop. So far, the
strategy is working _ Washington has scored 89 or more points in
each of its three victories.

"We share the ball, we work hard and we take open shots,''
Stanley said. "I want the players to have a comfort level with the
up-tempo game. I want to be the guide, then get out of the way.''

After Indiana cut the margin to 28-24 on successive baskets by
Rita Williams and Catchings, Holdsclaw hit a pair of layups to
jump-start a 16-2 run that produced a 44-26 lead.

"She didn't look like she'd missed two games,'' Stanley said.
"She seamlessly stepped in to what we were doing.''

The Fever twice got within nine points in the second half, the
last time with 12:25 remaining on a basket by Kelly Schumacher.

McCray scored nine of her points in the second half, and
finished 4-for-9 from the field with three 3-pointers. But the
Mystics did a good job of bottling up their former all-star
teammate on the wing.

"We wanted to stay between her and the basket, give her one
shot and box her out,'' Holdsclaw said. "Nikki does a great job of
getting in the lane _ she always has a counter move. We wanted to
contain her and not put her on the free throw line. I think we did
a good job of really making her an outside shooter.''
